Report: act_report¶

From the data which was gathered, assessed and cleaned by me, i was able to produce useful insights using some of the qualities showing relationships. Some of the insights are as follows:

What dog_breed is the most popular among tweets?¶

I filtered the final cleaned dataset by the dog breed column, a column i pulled out from the initial predictions column(p1,p2 and p3) in the image predictions table. I then used the observation to plot a barchart showing the least dog breeds that were tweeted about and the most tweeted about ones. From the dataset, it can be observed that the golden retriever was the breed that was tweeted about the most. Find the tweets with the most and least favorites counts?¶

For this part of my analysis, i compared the maximum and minimum favorite and retweet counts to get results. The most favorited twee had the picture below attached to it and was contained in this tweet "Here's a super supportive puppo participating in the Toronto #WomensMarch today. 13/10"

The tweet withthe most retweets from my dataset was of a dog standing in a pool and the tweet quoted "Here's a doggo realizing you can stand in a pool. 13/10 enlightened af (vid by Tina Conrad)".

The tweet with the least favorites and retweet counts are the same with the tweet content being "Oh my. Here you are seeing an Adobe Setter giving birth to twins!!! The world is an amazing place. 11/10". The image below is a visual representation of the tweet.

What time of the day is the account most active?¶

For my next analysis, i queried the dataset to find out what time of day traffic is usually at its peak for the we rate dogs account. In doing that, I used the pd.cut function to assign the timestamp into bins and created a new column to contain the results. After plotting the chart, it was observed that the time of day when the account posts the most tweets overtime is the twilight period(the hours between 12:00am and 6:00am).
